{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491468"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"950"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/950"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.13,0.61,0.08,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43270"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/950"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28263"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"},{"type":"tags","id":"3457"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11209"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43270"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents with a six-month history of dysphagia and regurgitation. He has a medical history of poorly controlled heartburn and hyperlipidaemia. His medications include proton pump inhibitor and simvastatin, which he typically forgets to take. He is a non-smoker, walks 2km every day and can walk up two flights of stairs without any problems. Physical examination is unremarkable. A contrast study with serial images is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peroral endoscopic myotomy","Nifedipine","Oesophageal dilatation","Laparoscopic cardiomyotomy","Laparoscopic fundoplication"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has a peptic stricture above a hiatus hernia. His background is highly suggestive of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD), which may induce strictures via the inflammatory response to acid in the lower oesophagus, and which can be exacerbated in the presence of a hiatus hernia. Strictures are now uncommon due to the widespread use and effectiveness of proton pump inhibitors in gastric acid suppression. However, in this scenario, the patient has poor medication compliance resulting in reflux that is poorly controlled\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this patient with stricture is \u003Cstrong\u003Edilatation. \u003C/strong\u003EDepending on how he responds to this, he might be considered for further surgical management. This might include a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Efundoplication\u003C/strong\u003E procedure to reduce further reflux - but his age and general fitness would need to be taken into consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cardiomyotomy \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E peroral endoscopic myotomy (POEM)\u003C/strong\u003E are procedures performed for achalasia and are not an appropriate form of management for stricture formation secondary to GORD. Achalasia is a condition where the lower oesophagus fails to contract properly, hindering the passage of food and fluid into the stomach. Both procedures involve cutting the muscles of the lower oesophageal sphincter to enable passage of food but differ in terms of their procedural approach i.e. laparoscopic vs endoscopic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENifedipine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a calcium channel blocker that can reduce the tone of the lower oesophageal sphincter. However, this would worsen GORD symptoms resulting in further esophageal exposure to gastric acid and worsening stricture formation, and is therefore not an appropriate management option for this patient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["With the effectiveness of current acid-suppressing agents, it is relatively easy to treat oesophageal peptic strictures with minimal intervention (dilatation)."],"references":["Maret-Ouda J, Brusselaers N, Lagergren J. What is the most effective treatment for severe gastro-oesophageal reflux disease? BMJ. 2015;350:h3169. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26108963/","Falk G, Katzka DA. Diseases of the Esophagus. Goldman-Cecil Medicine. 129, 859-870.e1","Gastrointestinal - Disorders of the oesophagus. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Ishikawa, Hisagi \u0026 Iwakiri, Katsuhiko \u0026 Sugiura, Toshiaki \u0026 Kobayashi, Masafumi. (2000). Effect of nifedipine administration (10mg) on esophageal acid exposure time. Journal of gastroenterology. 35. 43-6. 10.1007/s005350050008."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28263"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"950"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14438"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14438"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/df637d17-6049-47df-ba26-24eb84be5006.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/df637d17-6049-47df-ba26-24eb84be5006.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":529,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28263","links":{"self":"https://app